Objective

for each individual in the study, get the model-predicted Cmin, Cmax, and AUC at steady state for the randomized dose administration

  • We use empirical Bayes estimates that come out of the NONMEM run
  • There are multiple doses and infusion durations represented in the data; we need to get the right doses to the right individuals
  • Simulate out 4 doses should be enough
  • Calculate AUC by trapezoidal rule; use the parametric AUC calculation as a QC check

Load input data

Load the meropenem partab file

tab <- read_table(a$mero_partab, skip=1)

We create a data frame with one ID per row including each individual’s PK parameters

idata <- distinct(tab,ID,CL,V1,Q,V2)

Load the meropenem data set

data <- read_csv(a$mero_datafile, na='.')
names(data)[1] <- "ID"

And do some grooming - Take only dosing records - meropenem is dosing every 8 hours - simulate a total of 12 doses - for IV administration, pick compartment 2

dose <- filter(data, EVID==1)

This is important: we derive a DOSE column so that we can work with the simulated data according to dose group later on

data %<>% mutate(DOSE = AMT, DUR = AMT/RATE)

Load a 2-cmt model

Just take a model from the library

mod <- mread("pk2", modlib())

see(mod)

We should inventory the parameters in the model against what is in the data set

inventory(mod,data)

Easy enough to fix

data %<>% rename(V3 = V2, V2 = V1) %>% mutate(V1 = NULL)

inventory(mod,data)

The model we are using includes a extravascular dosing compartment with first order absorption controlled by parameter KA. Our drug is administered IV so it’s ok that we’re missing KA in the data set.

Not required … but I update the model with the parameters from the first individual to have a set of “valid” parameters in the model. Sometimes this helps when trying to get a sense check about whether the simulation is set up correctly or not.

mod %<>% update(param=data[1,])

des <- tgrid(0, 24, 0.5) + 3*24

So, let’s summarize.

sims <- as_data_frame(out)

Calculate AUC by trapezoidal rule

auc <- 
  sims %>% 
  AUC(., dv = "CP") %>% 
  dplyr::rename(tAUC = AUC) %>%
  as_data_frame

Recall that we carried CL into the simulated data. Let’s calculate AUC through CL and DOSE to see how it matches up

auc2 <- 
  sims %>%
  distinct(ID,DOSE,CL) %>%
  mutate(pAUC = 3*DOSE/CL) %>% 
  ungroup

auc2

Calculate Cmin and Cmax

minmax <- sims %>% 
  group_by(ID,DOSE,DUR) %>% 
  summarise(Cmin = min(CP), Cmax = max(CP)) %>% 
  ungroup

Join together and re-shape

sum <- left_join(auc, minmax) %>% left_join(.,auc2)

summ <- tidyr::gather(sum, variable, value, c(tAUC,pAUC,Cmin,Cmax))

Summary of exposure metrics

summ %>% 
  ungroup %>%
  group_by(DOSE,DUR,variable) %>%
  summarise(Med = median(value), 
            Mean = mean(value),
            Min = min(value),
            Max = max(value),
            N=n())  %>% as_data_frame
